  <div slot="quick-answer">
    <p><strong>Quick Answer:</strong> Choose Chardonnay when you want more body, texture, and a stronger fit for roast chicken, creamy sauces, or richer seafood. Choose Sauvignon Blanc when you want higher acidity, more freshness, and a better fit for shellfish, salads, herbs, and lighter dishes.</p>
  </div>

  <p>Chardonnay and Sauvignon Blanc are both white-wine staples, but they are rarely trying to do the same job. Chardonnay is usually broader and more flexible in texture. Sauvignon Blanc is usually sharper, lighter, and more obviously refreshing. Once you know whether you want richness or cut, the decision is usually easy.</p>

  <h2>Head-To-Head Comparison</h2>
  <div class="overflow-x-auto bg-wine-50 p-4 rounded-lg">
    <table class="w-full border-collapse">
